      "id":"culture/2013/oct/07/kakadu-tv-review",
      "sectionId":"culture",
      "sectionName":"Culture",
      "webPublicationDate":"2013-10-07T00:27:31Z",
      "webTitle":"Kakadu – TV review",
      "webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/culture/2013/oct/07/kakadu-tv-review",
      "apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/culture/2013/oct/07/kakadu-tv-review",
      "fields":{
        "trailText":"The ABC's new series following the guardians of the national park shows Kakadu at its most beautiful &ndash; and most dangerous",
        "headline":"Kakadu – TV review",
        "body":"<p><a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Surabaya\">Surabaya</a>, <a href=\"http://www.lonelyplanet.com/madagascar/antananarivo\">Antantanarivo</a>, <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Quelimane\">Quelimane</a> – exotic places with names evoking mystique and a sense of adventure. How about <a href=\"http://www.environment.gov.au/parks/kakadu/\">Kakadu</a> – or Gaagudju as it was known before white settlement?</p> <p>It’s a name which conjures images of wilderness where time is oblivious to the protocols of place names or designations such as World Heritage Site. It is, nonetheless, a domain sensitive to the effects of too much love or too little respect. The nearby monolith, Uluru has also been classified a globally significant site where ancient culture now amazes and provokes visitors from around the world.</p> <p>This new four-part series (<strong>ABC1, Sundays 7.30pm</strong>), narrated by Tom E Lewis and superbly photographed by Luke Petersen and Nick Robinson, offers an intensely personal view of the area through the activities of people entrusted with maintaining its integrity while simultaneously providing access to its wonders.</p> <p>The first thing to become obvious as the exploration unfolds, is that those who manage and protect the land are superbly attuned to the physical and the spiritual concerns of the work. This is stewardship of a natural resource upheld with unswerving belief and sensitivity for the balance between careful exploitation and preservation for the future.</p> <p>“Our land is our life, we have to protect it forever” says one savvy ranger. “Money doesn’t mean anything to me” says Jeffery Lee, a traditional owner. &quot;Money cars and jobs, they come and go. The land doesn’t go anywhere…”</p> <p>Fair enough. Tourists, while generating income, are essentially the most vulnerable and least necessary element in a complex eco-structure involving insects, microscopic creatures, plants, animals, reptiles, birds and aquatic animals such as the formidable saltwater crocodiles which have survived the searing heat and flooding rains of the region for millions of years.</p> <p>World Heritage listing of Kakadu, which is one third the size of Tasmania and half the size of Switzerland, began in 1981 and was formally completed in 1992.</p> <figure class=\"element element-image\" data-media-id=\"gu-fc-9f498b12-8245-46a7-9a98-1f6fd23f0190\"> <img src=\"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2013/10/6/1381034430611/9adc0f26-ce3f-4949-b2a0-c982c0a7e08c-460x276.jpeg\" alt=\"Jeff Lee Kakadu\" width=\"460\" height=\"276\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption>Jeffrey Lee: &quot;Money cars and jobs, they come and go. The land doesn’t go anywhere…”&nbsp;Photograph: /ABC</figcaption> </figure> <p>About 500 people live within its borders but upwards of 250,000 visitors come to the region annually and their safety is a key thread through the series - seen through the work of wildlife officers charged with ensuring crystal clear escarpment rivers and murky billabongs aren’t reservoirs of disasters for the unwary or outright foolish that are arrogant enough to turn a blind eye to the bleeding obvious. They occasionally end up&nbsp;<em>as</em>&nbsp;the bleeding obvious.</p> <p>Traditional owners such as Jeffery Lee can see beyond these clear and present dangers to the long-term peril of permitting insensitive and greedy operators to ruin the place. How uranium mines can be condoned inside Kakadu is as much a cause for bewilderment as the natural wonders which constitute the real wealth of the park.</p> <p>Viewers join cheerful botanists, environmental scientists, anthropolgists and rangers – not your standard Steve Irwin model – and naturalists such as Anne O’Dea and Ian Morris as they patrol.</p> <p>Fire is one of the elements that defines Kakadu. It can serve man and, equally, place him in grave jeopardy – as illustrated during an encounter with Steve Anderson, Jabiru’s fire officer and his band of “Angels”.</p> <p>They tackle a potentially lethal&nbsp;blaze – probably started by an unextinguished campfire – threatening their community. The stewards of Kakadu also have to deal with man-made disasters such as the devastation created by the misguided introduction of cane toads into Queensland in 1935. As a consequence no king brown snakes or giant spotted goannas, previously prolific, can be seen in 200 X 100 km park. Other species at risk, like the Northern Quoll, are being trained to avoid the toads and their toxic venom.</p> <p>It’s a salutary example of the balance of Nature being upset. Humans can at least be steered into compliance or obedience, and recreational anglers coming to fish for Barramundi or crabs find the law is enforced rigorously – a little too decently you might think after a confrontation between rangers Garry Lindner, his offsider, Andrew Wellings, and a boofheaded poacher.</p> <p>There are moments when the series veers into the style of reality documentary where actuality is accentuated and over-dramatised but by and large, the overwhelming reality of the place defines an eminently watchable series.</p><!-- Guardian Watermark: internal-code/content/419167641|2013-10-07T10:05:55Z|dcdf731fab828e6d4db67330bab8d57da2595ac8 -->",
