      "sectionId":"culture",
      "sectionName":"Culture",
      "webPublicationDate":"2013-10-05T23:05:28Z",
      "webTitle":"All My Sons – review",
      "webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/culture/2013/oct/06/all-my-sons-review",
      "apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/culture/2013/oct/06/all-my-sons-review",
      "fields":{
        "newspaperPageNumber":"27",
        "trailText":"A small businessman is forced to engage with society in a passionate version of Arthur Miller's play, writes <strong>Clare Brennan</strong>",
        "headline":"All My Sons – review",
        "body":"<p>It hadn't occurred to me that there might be any issues attached to this Royal Exchange co-production with the black-led theatre company <a href=\"http://www.talawa.com/\" title=\"\">Talawa </a> of American playwright Arthur Miller's 1947 play. Then I read the correspondence on <a href=\"http://www.royalexchange.co.uk/event.aspx?id=717\" title=\"\">the Exchange's website</a>. People wondered whether the play would have to be directorially adjusted to accommodate a non-white cast. As far as I could see, Michael Buffong (who directed the award-winning production of Lorraine Hansberry's <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/stage/2010/feb/14/raisin-in-the-sun-hansberry\" title=\"\"><em>A Raisin in the Sun</em></a> for the Exchange in 2010) has made no changes to the text, nor were any necessary: skin colour is not Miller's theme; ideological orientation is.</p><p>A small businessman discovers that, to be fully human, he must look beyond the narrow limits of making money for his immediate family. In Miller's work, there is such a thing as society and we are all answerable to it. (I wonder: how many of the supposedly arts-loving Conservative party thronging the city visited the theatre during their conference visit?)When Don Warrington's Joe is finally forced to acknowledge that the strangers destroyed by his self-protective self-interest are \"all my sons\", the production reaches an intensity that fuses his statement into a declaration that is both emotionally wrenching and rationally convincing. Warrington is tremendous in this last act. So are Doña Croll, his ghost-haunted wife, and Chiké Okonkwo, his upright but blinkered surviving son. Each shatters the accretions of lies that have carapaced their characters with devastating precision.</p><p>On press night, the first two acts were less assured. Ellen Carins's set looks good, with its clapboard porch, garden benches and fallen apple tree (symbolically hinting at the lies that thread the play). But the dappled green lawn of the yard seemed too big for the actors, who fidgeted about trying to hit a collective rhythm. In a cast of 10, eight were making a first appearance at this demanding theatre in the round. It felt as if, as a company, they hadn't yet quite mastered the space. Hence, three stars on our new rating system. Given the quality of individual performances, though, I would expect that, by the time this review is published, it will be four (or more?).</p><!-- Guardian Watermark: internal-code/content/418983312|2013-10-07T10:05:55Z|21fd04ac1aaf882df6d8fcceb670a02ae723de1d -->",
