      "id":"culture/2013/oct/04/miley-cyrus-bangerz-review",
      "sectionId":"culture",
      "sectionName":"Culture",
      "webPublicationDate":"2013-10-04T12:20:00Z",
      "webTitle":"Miley Cyrus: Bangerz – review",
      "webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/culture/2013/oct/04/miley-cyrus-bangerz-review",
      "apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/culture/2013/oct/04/miley-cyrus-bangerz-review",
      "fields":{
        "newspaperPageNumber":"32",
        "trailText":"<p>Miley Cyrus's attempts to shock would be more effective if she had songs to back up the posturing, writes <strong>Kitty Empire</strong></p>",
        "headline":"Miley Cyrus: Bangerz – review",
        "body":"<p>Over-exposure has been a hot topic in pop discourse of late. Anyone holding Haim's current media ubiquity against them, though, might do well to contemplate the stranglehold on tittle-tattle and moral outrage exercised by one singer from Tennessee. She is currently embroiled in an <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/culture/2013/oct/03/miley-cyrus-prostitute-warns-sinead-oconnor\">ugly exchange with Sinéad O'Connor</a> over her raunchy image. Those easily shocked by calculation in pop should look away now.</p><p>Last spring, Miley Cyrus dropped a song called We Can't Stop. In tandem with its <a href=\"http://www.muzu.tv/miley-cyrus/we-cant-stop-music-video/1923501/\" title=\"\">ribald video</a>, it did unspeakable things to the memory of Hannah Montana, the tween star once played by Cyrus. A party anthem, this album's lead single endorses ecstasy (\"dancing with Molly\") and twerking, essentially the 21st-century US urban version of \"slack\" Jamaican dancehall moves. If the song sounds like a Rihanna number, <a href=\"http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop-shop/1566461/miley-cyrus-we-cant-stop-originally-intended-for-rihanna\" title=\"\">that's because it nearly was</a>. When Cyrus twerked at MTV's Video Music awards back in August, <a href=\"http://www.entertainmentwise.com/news/125139/Miley-Cyrus-Raunchy-VMAs-Performance-Helps-Star-Gain-213104-Twitter-Followers-And-Sell-90000-Downloads\" title=\"\">her social media profile increased 112%</a>, according to <em>Forbes</em> magazine. Then there was the video for Wrecking Ball, a power-ballad turbo-charged by the fact that Cyrus is starkers for much of the video, sometimes licking a mallet.</p><p>To coincide with the release of <em>Bangerz</em>, her fourth album, MTV US screened a documentary, <em>Miley Cyrus: The Movement</em>, that purported to show how <a href=\"http://www.spin.com/articles/mtv-miley-cyrus-the-movement-documentary/\" title=\"\">this brouhaha has been gleefully choreographed by a stage brat-turned-wild child</a>, one with a gimlet eye on the big time, whose last album – 2010's <em>Can't Be Tamed</em> – pretty much flopped. When it's not an almighty attention-seeking device, <em>Bangerz</em> is an album about very public heartbreak. In an announcement that chimed fortuitously with the build-up to <em>Bangerz</em>'s release, it was recently confirmed that Cyrus's four-year relationship with actor Liam Hemsworth is no more.</p><p>Against big odds, this craven album actually begins with the calm musical resolution of Adore You, a bid for the listener's sympathy, and one of its least showy and most successful cuts. Here are unhurried beats, a few chords and Cyrus's languorous vocal, \"ah\"-ing and \"hey\"-ing into a song about power imbalance in love.</p><p>As the title suggests, another heartbreak track, FU, is less resolved, but just as interesting. Here, Cyrus liberates her inner Christina Aguilera in the company of rapper French Montana, blending old-time jazzy balladry, I Put a Spell on You, romantic righteousness and dubstep sub-bass. Including recent US No 1 Wrecking Ball, the heartbreak section of <em>Bangerz</em> mostly repays your attention. More intriguing genre experiments follow – not least My Darlin', essentially a pimped-up version of Ben E King's Stand By Me.</p><p>But for all the mash-ups, <em>Bangerz</em> feels stitched together in the dark, and the attention-seeking begins to grate. Setting aside the sexual content of Cyrus's recent oeuvre, the crux of the internet chat has been her new fetish for R&amp;B and southern hip-hop. This really is not the first time a Southern white singer has appropriated poses first developed in African-American contexts (Elvis, Justin Timblerlake), or, indeed, the first time a former teen pop starlet has turned to R&amp;B for a raunchy style reboot (Aguilera, Britney Spears). Pharrell Williams, who mentored Cyrus through the project, is sympathetic (\"Why is she twerking?… She's a product of America,\" he says), but others feel uncomfortable with the <a href=\"http://www.waywordradio.org/ghetto_pass/\" title=\"\">\"ghetto pass\"</a> Cyrus has issued herself, like so much fake ID.</p><p>It might be a different story if many of the hip-hop- and R&amp;B-inspired cuts were better. SMS (Bangerz) is a bad rip-off of Salt-N-Pepa's Push It, with a phoned-in Britney guest spot. Love Money Party, meanwhile, finds Cyrus rapping a series of non-sequitur buzzwords, gibberish loosely connected by a bit of production, driven by the inescapable purpose of <em>Bangerz</em>: a desire to wind people up for commercial, rather than transgressive, ends.</p><!-- Guardian Watermark: internal-code/content/418843838|2013-10-07T10:05:55Z|ff9b832b68b1114a94add370d9a15bd0013e4cc1 -->",
