        "newspaperPageNumber":"8",
        "trailText":"<p><strong>Rachel Cooke</strong>'s new book re-examines 10 pioneering 1950s women. In this extract she tells the stories of Muriel and Betty Box, two prominent women in the British film industry</p>",
        "headline":"Power women of the 1950s: Muriel and Betty Box",
        "body":"<p>Until recently, anyone who wanted to see the film <em>To Dorothy a Son </em>had to lock themselves deep in the bowels of the British Film Institute off Tottenham Court Road, London, and watch it on an old Steenbeck editing machine. A little-known comedy from 1954, <em>To Dorothy</em> is no one's idea of a classic. It has an infuriating star in Shelley Winters, a creaky screenplay by Peter Rogers (later the producer of the <em>Carry On</em> series) and a set that looks as if it is on loan from a local amateur dramatics society.</p><p>We are in the home of Tony (John Gregson) and his baby-faced wife, Dorothy (Peggy Cummins). Dorothy is heavily pregnant, and confined to bed. Tony is a composer with a deadline to meet, bailiffs to keep at bay and, thanks to the condition of his wife, a home to run. The house is a mess: when the telephone rings it can't be found beneath the piles of paper. Then, just to make things even more chaotic, Tony's American ex-wife, Myrtle (Winters), turns up, bearing the news that she will inherit her uncle's $2m fortune if, by a certain date, her former husband has not yet produced a son. There follows, as the film's poster had it, \"a riot\". Myrtle is desperate that Dorothy does not give birth until her legacy is safe. Tony, meanwhile, is panicking about another of her announcements – thanks to a clerical error, they may not have been divorced. It's all quite silly. In the end, though, Tony discovers that he and Myrtle were not married at all; Dorothy gives birth to twins, a girl and a boy, the latter arriving just after the deadline has passed; Myrtle decides to share her legacy, thus solving Tony and Dorothy's money worries once and for all. Hooray! Let the titles roll.</p><p>But something dark is at play beneath this surface fluff. In 1954, the divorce rate was six times what it had been before the war. Countless women, moreover, were involved in phoney second \"marriages\", their surnames changed by deed poll the better to make them appear respectable. Many people believed that marriage was in crisis. <em>To Dorothy a Son </em>reflects this anxiety. It's all here: the untimely reappearance of a first wife/husband; the dread exposure of a bigamous/sham marriage and its shameful consequence, illegitimacy; the painful postwar recalibration of the roles of men and women. Even as Dorothy makes demands on Tony, she fears his resentment. \"I don't want the baby,\" she tells him. \"I hate babies.\" But what she really hates, you suspect, is her own powerlessness – and, perhaps, the sight of her husband running around in an apron.</p><p>\"Men were made to wear the pants, and the pants were made to carry the dough,\" says Myrtle sarcastically, amused by the change in her ex. But she only half means it. After years as a struggling singer, Myrtle is thrilled to have her own money to spend: if Dorothy has two babies, she will have two mink coats. Hunkered in my screening room for one at the BFI, it was with some amazement that I realised the two women would end as friends, not rivals – a weirdly feminist twist in a film whose female characters are mere archetypes. Myrtle splits her inheritance not in half but three ways, and in doing so silently asks the question of the hour: why should only Tony escape the tyranny of the feather duster?</p><figure data-media-id='gu-image-419081765'><img src='http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Admin/BkFill/Default_image_group/2013/10/4/1380888051049/John-Gregson-Shelley-Wint-001.jpg' alt='John Gregson, Shelley Winters and Peggy Cummins in To Dorothy a Son (1954).' width='460' height='275' class='gu-image'/><figcaption>John Gregson, Shelley Winters and Peggy Cummins in To Dorothy a Son (1954). Photograph: BFI</figcaption></figure><p>Every year, during the film awards season, the cry goes up: where are all the women? But in Britain, in 1954, they were everywhere. It's hardly surprising that <em>To Dorothy a Son</em> came with a subliminal feminist message, for its director was <a href=\"http://www.screenonline.org.uk/people/id/479374/\" title=\"\">Muriel Box</a>, a passionate feminist. Amazingly, this was her second picture of the year. Even as she was shooting it – Shelley Winters driving her round the bend with her refusal ever to learn her lines – she was editing <a href=\"http://www.tcm.com/mediaroom/video/174029/Beachcomber-The-Original-Trailer-.html\" title=\"\"><em>The Beachcomber</em></a>, a drama starring Glynis Johns filmed on location&nbsp;in&nbsp;Ceylon.</p><p>Alas, neither <em>The Beachcomber</em> nor <em>To Dorothy </em>was a hit for Box: \"Spent nearly £8 on a pair of evening shoes… shocking!!!\" she wrote in her diary, having spent a consolatory day shopping after the \"lousy\" reviews for the latter. Many of her colleagues, however, were having better luck. <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/stage/2010/feb/28/wendy-toye-obituary\" title=\"\">Wendy Toye</a>, a recent winner of the prize for best short film at Cannes, had directed a respectable if rather baggy thriller, <em>The Teckman Mystery</em>, starring Margaret Leighton. A former debutante called Joan Henry had adapted her bestselling prison memoir, <em>Who Lie in Gaol</em>, for the director J Lee Thompson, and the result – <a href=\"http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=TH61nx6KyFE\" title=\"\"><em>The Weak and the Wicked</em></a>, starring Glynis Johns as a gambling addict – had grossed £200,000 at the box office. <a href=\"http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=p1EFOWjMGAY\" title=\"\"><em>The Belles of St Trinian's</em></a>, the third most popular film of the year, had been edited by the brilliant Thelma Connell.</p><p>Most stunning of all, though, was the success of Betty Box, the sister of Muriel's husband, Sydney. Betty had produced the hit <a href=\"http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=oVWjAeAa52o\" title=\"\"><em>Doctor in the House</em></a>, which had made a star of Dirk Bogarde, whom she'd cast as the duffle-coated student Simon Starling in the face of stiff opposition from her bosses at Rank. \"An uproarious, devil-may-care, almost wholly ruthless picture of the goings-on in medical training at a London hospital,\" the critic <a href=\"http://www.screenonline.org.uk/people/id/473849/\" title=\"\">Dilys Powell </a>had written of it. Oh, yes. That's another thing: women film critics were 10 a penny. The most famous were Powell at the <em>Sunday Times </em>and <a href=\"http://www.screenonline.org.uk/people/id/463484/\" title=\"\">CA Lejeune </a>at the <em>Observer</em>, but there were others too: E Arnot Robertson at the <em>Daily Mail</em>, Isabel Quigly at the <em>Spectator</em>, <a href=\"http://www.powell-pressburger.org/Reviews/45_IKWIG/Contemporary/Sketch.html\" title=\"\"><em>Elspeth Grant</em></a>on the <em>Daily Sketch</em>. In 1956 a woman, Penelope Houston, was appointed editor of <em>Sight and Sound</em>, the journal of the British Film&nbsp;Institute.</p><p><a href=\"http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=oVWjAeAa52o\">Reading this on mobile? Click here to watch video</a></p><p>Muriel Box was a curious mixture: easily disheartened yet doggedly ambitious. When she heard that the distributors of <em>To Dorothy</em>, her fifth film, would not be giving it a West End run, she fell into a depression. But she also knew the territory. You had to keep going. The one thing that she and Wendy Toye, Joan Henry, Thelma Connell and her sister- in-law Betty had in common, apart from their sex, was that they ate setbacks for breakfast. It wasn't only the men who were against you (<a href=\"http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=h9HSqKgmRAM\" title=\"\">Michael Balcon</a>, who ran Ealing Studios, would tell anyone who would listen that women lacked the qualities to control a film unit). Some women were too. Kay Kendall, soon to appear in Muriel's film<em> </em><a href=\"http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Dl8F_rMiH9c\" title=\"\"><em>Simon and Laura</em></a><em>,</em> would say that it had felt \"strange and uncomfortable\" to be directed by Box; Muriel Pavlow, her co-star, insisted \"I respond better to a male director\".</p><p>The other thing Muriel had by the bucketload was experience. She was 49 by the time she made <em>To Dorothy</em>, and had been working in the film industry for almost 25 years. On her sideboard at home stood the Oscar she and  Sydney had won in 1946 for the screenplay of <a href=\"http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=uu1PHOZ9LGM\" title=\"\"><em>The Seventh Veil</em></a>, a film starring James Mason that was one of the first pictures to take psychiatry seriously. But thrilled though she'd been to receive it, the distinct sense of anti-climax she felt when the statuette arrived from Hollywood in a straw-filled packing case had turned out to be something of a portent. Three years later she directed her first feature, <em>The Lost People</em>, and the reviews were \"foul\". It was, she thought, probably best not to take anything too seriously. If the doldrums could follow hard on the heels of an Academy Award, then a flop could be succeeded just as swiftly by a smash hit.</p><figure data-media-id='gu-image-419081766'><img src='http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Observer/Columnist/Columnists/2013/10/3/1380811810002/muriel-box-at-camera-001.jpg' alt='muriel box at camera' width='180' height='200' class='gu-image'/><figcaption>Muriel Box behind the camera during the making of The Truth about Women. Photograph: Popperfoto/Getty Images</figcaption></figure><p><strong>Violette Muriel Baker </strong>was born in 1905, in New Malden, Surrey, the daughter of a railway clerk. It was when war broke out in 1914 that she fell for the movies. With everyone at home preoccupied with food, or rather the lack of it, she lived only for her visits to the cinema: \"It was the heyday of the cliff-hanging serials, the one- and two-reel slapstick comedies, and the flickering newsreels. King Edward VII's funeral was the most impressive spectacle we had ever seen.\" When an old friend of her mother's offered the family free seats for any show they cared to see in the picture house he ran, Muriel took him at his word, presenting herself twice weekly at its door. For a while, this was tolerated. One day, however, she was shown a wooden chair on the stage behind the screen and told that from now on this was where she would watch the film. It wasn't ideal: the whirring of the projector almost drowned out the music from the orchestra pit. But there were advantages: when the show was over she was sometimes allowed to rewind the spools, and if the film had broken the projectionist would let her help him stick it together again. Even better, she was allowed to take home the frames that were \"lost' in the course of this operation.</p><p>Muriel's father thought she should train as a shorthand typist, but she had other ideas. \"I want to go on the films,\" she told her parents. It seemed an impossible dream, but in the summer of 1920, the films unwittingly came to her. On a train to Southsea to visit her grandmother, she fell into conversation with a stranger. He asked if she liked the movies – she had her nose deep in her favourite magazine, <em>Picture Show </em>– and when she told him that yes, she did, he plied her with questions. As the train pulled in, he handed Muriel his card; if ever she wanted to see a film being made, she should give him a ring.</p><p>\"JOSEPH GROSSMAN\", she read. And then the miraculous words: \"STOLL PICTURE PRODUCTIONS\". Muriel knew all about Stoll, where Grossman was studio manager. Its latest film, <em>The Glorious Adventure</em>, a melodrama about the Great Fire of London, was being shot in a new colour process called Prizma and starred Lady Diana Manners, the society beauty. And so it was that six months later she made the first of what would be several visits to Cricklewood, the home of Stoll. Muriel was too shy to broach the subject of a job, and in any case her meagre wardrobe, which consisted only of her school gym tunic, the bridesmaid's dress she had worn at her sister's wedding and one old skirt, would barely have seen her through the week. But eventually Grossman gave her, unprompted, a few days' crowd work.</p><p>Back at home, she eagerly enrolled at the Margaret Barnes School of Dancing in Surbiton, and signed up for classes with Sir Ben Greet, the Shakespearean actor-manager. But there was trouble ahead. Muriel had fallen in love with an associate of her father's, Stanley. He was 14 years her senior and her parents thought him wildly unsuitable. When her mother began censoring her post, Muriel put everything she owned into a bag and headed for Welwyn Garden City, where her sister's mother-in-law had offered her a room. There, she found a position as a secretary at Barclays Corsets.</p><p>Two long years passed. In 1929 Muriel landed a new job at <a href=\"http://www.screenonline.org.uk/film/id/543966/\" title=\"\">British Instructional Films</a>, as a secretary in the Scenario Department: \"Life suddenly became very interesting and unpredictable. Everything was in a state of flux, the company turning over from silent pictures to 'talkies', an operation fraught with anxiety and many pitfalls.\" It was a while before producers realised they would need to hire dramatists to craft dialogue – at first they stuck with the scenarists who'd written the subtitles that accompanied the silent movies – and this gave Muriel an opportunity: directors would sometimes accept her suggestions for improvements to the scripts she typed up. She got another break when the continuity girl on Puffin Asquith's first talkie, a drama about Gallipoli called <em>Tell England</em>, fell ill with appendicitis. Asked to step in until a substitute could be found, Muriel worked on the film for the next three weeks. But no sooner had it wrapped than she found herself back at her desk, and soon after this a third of BIF's staff were laid off, Muriel among them: the silent films the company had on its stocks could not now find distributors, and its debts had piled up.</p><p>For a while she worked as a freelance continuity girl, bluffing her way through her first few films, until, in 1932, she joined Michael Powell's company in Wardour Street (Powell was then directing \"quota quickies\"). Tired of train journeys, she found herself an attic in a house overlooking Regent's Park. The room was not luxurious – water had to be hauled upstairs in a bucket, her underwear washed in a pan on the stove – and she was very lonely. \"The utter blankness which confronts one on trying to be self-sufficient and philosophical,\" she confided to her diary. In an effort to lift herself out of this depression, she auditioned for Rada: her final stab at the big time. But when the day arrived and she launched into Mirabell's speech from Congreve's <em>The Way of the World</em>, her courage ebbed, replaced with \"a suffocating, creeping despair which, three quarters of the way through, literally choked me\". Back in her room, she cried for several hours: \"My last chance! And I had muffed it!\"</p><p><a href=\"http://www.britmovie.co.uk/directors/Sydney-Box\" title=\"\">Sydney Box</a> was an aspiring playwright whose roots were even humbler than Muriel's. \"I still shudder at the memory of one period of two weeks when our [childhood] diet consisted solely of porridge, boiled swedes and cocoa,\" he would recall later. Having begun his working life as a cub reporter on the <em>Kentish Times</em>, he was by the early 1930s a Fleet Street freelance. But he lived in Beckenham, his home town, where he wrote and produced plays for the local dramatic society. He was shy, balding, generous, easy-going, flirtatious, a wheeler-dealer, energetic, full of ideas, lame in one leg, and married.</p><figure data-media-id='gu-image-419081767'><img src='http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Admin/BkFill/Default_image_group/2013/10/4/1380889649147/Muriel-Box-left-with-Shel-001.jpg' alt='Muriel Box, left, with Shelley Winters on the set of To Dorothy a Son, 1954 ' width='460' height='275' class='gu-image'/><figcaption>Muriel Box, left, with Shelley Winters on the set of To Dorothy a Son, 1954. Photograph: BFI</figcaption></figure><p>He and Muriel had been involved in a desultory correspondence since the summer of 1932, when his one-act play <em>Murder Trial </em>had won a prize at the Welwyn's drama festival (hearing of its brilliance, Muriel wrote asking if she might have a copy). But in 1933 things changed between them. Sydney was invited to dinner at the attic, where they spent most of the evening exchanging confidences. Muriel told him all about Stanley, and he told her all about his four-year marriage. It had been a mistake; he and his wife had not slept together for years; he was, he insisted, \"released from all obligations\".</p><p>Within a month she and Sydney were sleeping together. By the autumn they had found rooms to rent opposite a fried-fish shop in Bloomsbury. They were well suited, the one an incurable optimist (he), the other an incurable pessimist (she). \"I have a feeling our relationship will prove fruitful,\" she wrote in her diary. She wasn't wrong about this. One day soon afterwards, he arrived home with an even bigger grin than usual on his face. It had occurred to him that while the majority of Britain's amateur actors were women, most of the plays that were written with drama societies in mind had more parts for men, and on a sudden impulse he had walked into Harraps, the publishers, to tell them so. He had walked out again with a contract to produce a book of six one-act plays with all-women casts. In just three months.</p><p>And so it was that he and Muriel began working together – a partnership that would last for the next three decades. Every evening she would work on the first draft of a play they had roughed out over supper. She would then pass it to Sydney to polish. And on and on, until the work was done. The result, <em>Ladies Only</em>, and its follow-up, <em>Petticoat Plays</em>, were an instant success; over the course of the next six years they would publish upwards of 50 such dramas. No West End producer would have known either of their names, but the Boxes were soon the most performed playwrights in Britain.</p><p>For a while, life was good. Sydney and Muriel were married in May, 1935,  and their daughter, Leonora, was born the following year. But with the outbreak of war in 1939, the lights went out at Britain's amateur dramatic societies. Who was going to want their plays now? Again, it was Sydney who had the bright idea. What about a compendium of puzzles, jokes and poems to get families through the long nights ahead? <em>The Black-Out Book</em> was published in November 1939, and was so successful that on the back of its royalties Sydney was able to establish his own documentary company. Within two years Verity Films would be the biggest producer of government-sponsored propaganda in the country.</p><p>For the first months of the war, Muriel stayed in London. But once the bombing began, it was decided that she and Leonora would have to be evacuated. She feared missing out – \"It was obvious,\" she said later, \"that attitudes to everything were changing, mine included\" – and when she arrived in Dumfries after a 14-hour train journey, she felt she'd landed in another world. The only consolation was that she had her sister-in-law, Betty, for company (they occupied two rooms in the home of a shoe salesman): \"A petite, very pretty blonde, with an engaging manner which effectively disguised a remarkably keen brain.\" Hardly surprising, then, that when Sydney suggested Muriel might come to London to help him with a 90-minute documentary, <em>The Soldier's Food </em>– Ralph Richardson was to be seconded from the Fleet Air Arm to star – she did not hesitate. Leaving Leonora with her mother-in-law, she hot-footed it back to London.</p><p>Making this little film about messing committees and hay-box cooking took longer than expected: location work was hampered by the dive-bombing of Messerschmitts. Yet the experience only increased Muriel's determination to work. By this time Sydney had persuaded Betty, a trained commercial artist, to join Verity Films as a production assistant, and now he made his wife the director of a documentary for the British Council, <em>The English Inn</em>, the first of several Ministry of Information films she would make. Only when the ministry decreed that road safety for children was not a suitable project for a woman did this run end – by which time he needed Muriel elsewhere, for Sydney was branching into features, leaving Verity in the capable hands of Betty. In 1943, he acquired a lease on Riverside Studios and he and Muriel began working on the screenplay of their first independent production, an adaptation of the stage comedy <em>29 Acacia Avenue</em>.</p><p>It was surreal to be making films in the Blitz. But it was amazing how work could cause even the most terrible events to fade to grey. In 1944, London was under attack from the V1s, the devastating bombs known as doodlebugs. Muriel was exhausted; it was impossible to sleep. On fire-watch duty she had counted 30 flying bombs in a single evening. In Norwood, two of Sydney's relatives had been killed when a V2 – the doodlebug's successor – landed on their house. And yet, she noted, the greater part of her was preoccupied with <em>29 Acacia Avenue</em>, now wrapped, which J Arthur Rank was refusing to distribute (audience laughter at a screening had convinced him, a strict Methodist, that it was \"immoral\").</p><p><a href=\"http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=uu1PHOZ9LGM\">Reading this on mobile? Click here to watch video</a></p><p>The same was true of the shortages. It had been several years since Muriel had been able to get her hands on a pair of stockings, but she couldn't feel too glum. She and Sydney had written a melodrama about a suicidal pianist, <em>The Seventh Veil</em>, and it had gone into production starring Ann Todd and James Mason. On balance, she would probably take the movie over a pair of nylons – a deal that seemed even more of a bargain when <em>The Seventh Veil </em>opened on 22 October 1945 at the Leicester Square Odeon. Everyone loved it. The film would go on to win the Oscar for best original screenplay. It had cost just £92,000 to make. No wonder Arthur Rank now asked Sydney to take charge of production at Gainsborough Studios.</p><p>It was Noël Coward who – following their takeover at Gainsborough – described the Boxes as \"the Brontës of Shepherd's Bush\". But this was not entirely accurate. Betty Box, the member of the family for whom the Gainsborough years would prove to be most successful, worked not in Shepherd's Bush but at the studio's Islington outpost, where Sydney had appointed her the studio head.This was a shrewd move. Rank had contracted him to make 12 pictures a year; Islington's output would need to comprise roughly a quarter of this total if he was to meet these obligations. He needed to be sure its stages were productive, and what better way of doing so than by putting his own sister in charge? Overnight, then, Betty became Britain's leading female film producer – its only female producer – and at the age of 31. \"I quickly learnt what a very different world I was entering,\" she wrote. \"At Verity, I could say to the army, 'I'll need 300 private soldiers with their officers, a dozen tanks, a column of vehicles,' and they were all delivered without any charge (providing, of course, they weren't otherwise occupied dealing with Messrs Hitler and Mussolini). But now came big deals with stars, top technicians, composers, designers for huge sets and for film stars' clothes – a very much tougher proposition.\" Gainsborough's reputation was, famously, for melodrama. But Betty, believing that postwar audiences needed cheering up, now produced hit comedies such as <a href=\"http://www.screenonline.org.uk/film/id/487724/\" title=\"\"><em>Miranda</em></a>, in which a man takes a mermaid to see London disguised as an invalid in a wheelchair.</p><p>In 1949 Arthur Rank announced that he was closing the outmoded studios at Shepherd's Bush and Islington, and moving production to Pinewood in Buckinghamshire. For Betty, who would work at Pinewood for the next two decades, this was \"total luxury\". For Muriel, still marooned in script development, this meant another opportunity. <em>Cockpit</em>, a film Sydney had produced at Gainsborough, came with them to Pinewood, but was not thought fit for release. Rather than leave it on the shelf, he now decided to rewrite sections of the script – set in Germany after the war, it starred Richard Attenborough – and have them reshot in the hope of recouping some of his investment. This was, of course, a gig no well-known director would want. But Muriel was familiar with the material and would not even ask to be paid. The board, ordinarily violently opposed to the idea of a woman director, gave their consent.</p><p>Muriel reshot almost 60% of <em>Cockpit </em>(renamed <em>The Lost People </em>on release). On set with her she kept a Moviola – a miniature projection machine – to check the original footage for continuity against the scenes she was about to shoot. The experience was akin to \"solving an intricate film jigsaw\", and she knew \"it would never add up to much\". But she didn't care. \"Its importance was that it demonstrated to those who mattered that I had the ability to handle artists and dialogue as well as move my camera around.\"</p><p>In 1950 Sydney left Rank and set up his own company, London Independent Producers, his intention to make five pictures a year. The first of these was to be a low-budget adaptation of <em>The Happy Family</em>, a stage play about a grocery store on the proposed site of the Festival of Britain. At the casting stage, so as not to cause alarm, he told agents that he and Muriel would be co-directing (the large cast included Stanley Holloway and Dandy Nichols). But the moment shooting started he left her alone. For Muriel, this changed everything. The film made a substantial profit and picked up good reviews. The studios could now have no objection to her as a director, and she moved swiftly on to her next project: <em>Street Corner</em>, a drama-documentary about women in the police force.</p><figure data-media-id='gu-image-419081768'><img src='http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Admin/BkFill/Default_image_group/2013/10/4/1380888139221/Brigitte-Bardot-Betty-Box-001.jpg' alt='Brigitte Bardot, Betty Box, Dirk Bogarde and director Ralph Thomas, on the set of Doctor at Large' width='460' height='355' class='gu-image'/><figcaption>Brigitte Bardot, Betty Box, Dirk Bogarde and director Ralph Thomas, on the set of Doctor at Large, 1957. Photograph: Rex Features</figcaption></figure><p>The movies now came thick and fast. <em>Street Corner</em>, released in 1953, was followed by <em>The Beachcomber </em>and <em>To Dorothy a Son </em>in 1954, and they were followed by <em>Simon and Laura </em>(1955), <em>Eyewitness </em>(1956), <em>The Passionate Stranger </em>and <a href=\"http://www.tcm.com/mediaroom/video/457784/Truth-About-Women-The-Marooned-In-A-Lift.html\" title=\"\"><em>The Truth About Women</em></a><em> </em>(both 1957), <em>This Other Eden</em> and <em>Subway in the Sky</em> (both 1959). Muriel did not have a free hand when it came to the films she made. Budgets were tiny and schedules tight. Nor was she the most creative of directors. Her shots are prosaic, and her films often want for pace. But <em>Street Corner</em>, with its mostly female cast, was a groundbreaking film. So, too, was <em>Simon and Laura</em>,<em> </em>in which Kay Kendall and Peter Finch play married actors whose smug portrayal of a happy couple in a soap opera is in stark contrast to the reality at home. It satirises television, the coming medium, deftly and with&nbsp;great warmth.</p><p>Soon after Betty arrived at Pinewood in 1949, she met the director Ralph Thomas, whose thriller, <em>The Clouded Yellow</em>, she was to produce. This was a relationship that would endure for 30 films, but it wasn't only professional: Betty and Ralph would soon become lovers, too – a situation they managed according to the mores of the day. On location they were a couple. At home they went back to their real lives. Ralph had a wife, Joy, and two children. Betty had her husband, Peter Rogers. (Norman Hudis, the screenwriter, once asked Betty what she thought about having children. \"Oh, I can't be bothered,\" she said.) No one seemed unhappy. Joy was devoted to her young family. Peter had his own films to produce: the <em>Carry On</em> series, which were directed by Ralph's brother Gerald. And however complicated this arrangement, between them these two couples made about 100 movies, films that now read like an index of the varying fortunes of the British film industry from Kenneth More to Roger Moore.</p><p>Somebody in publicity once made the mistake of writing in a press release that Petula Clark would sing a \"little\" song in one of Betty's films. \"I never produce anything little,\" said Betty, putting a line through it. This is not to say that she was grand. In India to make <em>The Wind Cannot Read </em>(1958), she got the wardrobe department to build half a dozen pockets into her poncho, so that that she could hide bottles of whisky in them on India's dry days and keep the crew happy. Like her brother, she never forgot her hardscrabble childhood; she liked being rich and felt no need to apologise for it: \"I already owned five fur coats, so I ordered a white mink, floor length, and wore it with pleasure, even if it did make me look like I was rolling along on casters.\" And she was a famously tough negotiator. When she discovered that in spite of all she'd done for the company – by the mid-50s, her nickname was Betty Box Office – her fees were lower than those of Rank's male producers, she went to see its director, John Davis, and demanded the figures be \"adjusted'. Davis blustered. \"What do you need the money for? Another mink coat? You have a rich husband – you don't need a rise.\" By the time she removed herself from his office, however, her request had been \"amicably granted\".</p><p>In 1959, Sydney Box suffered a cerebral haemorrhage. While he rested, Muriel made only one picture: <em>The Piper's Tune</em>, for the Children's Film Foundation. He and Muriel made their last movie in 1964: <em>Rattle of a Simple Man</em>, a second-rate comedy about a naive young man (Harry H Corbett) who travels to London for the FA Cup, where he unwittingly falls in love with a prostitute. Betty's film career continued a little longer. Her last movie, directed by the stalwart Ralph, was the lamentable <em>Percy's Progress </em>in 1974. A sequel to <em>Percy</em>, it was a comedy about the recipient of the world's first penis transplant.</p><p>The Boxes' time had passed. They were middle-aged at a moment when the middle-aged suddenly seemed very old – a trend that the movies, as ever, ruthlessly exaggerated. First there had come the films of the new wave: <em>Room at the Top</em>, <em>Look Back in Anger</em>. Then London had begun to swing, and the films with it: <em>Georgy Girl</em> and <em>Darling</em>. Their gentle comedies, their plucky British affairs about love and war, were relics to be put away, like antimacassars and the novels of Nevil Shute.</p><p>Betty took this in her stride. She wafted around in a kaftan, and thought about the good times: \"I cherished them: the opportunity I was given to show that a woman could do the job as well as any man.\" For Muriel, things were more difficult. On 30 October 1964 the telephone rang, and though she somehow managed to stand at her hall table long enough to take a message, she felt as though she was falling. Sydney, it seemed, was having an affair. The flat in town he had been keeping as a writing den was a love nest, shared with a woman called Sylvia Knowles. Half mad with grief, she began to think. This man she had loved for so long: hadn't he always been disappearing to Brighton to hole up in a hotel while he rewrote his latest script? It was as if she'd been blind, and now she could see.</p><p>For a time she rallied. But over dinner at Maxim's in Paris in 1965, it only took one cool question on her part and several martinis on his for it all to come out. As if he was merely talking her through a casting list, Sydney now told her that he had never been faithful.</p><p>In 1966 Sydney suffered a heart attack. By now, Muriel was reduced to hounding her husband and Sylvia from afar. In 1967 they escaped her by moving to Australia, Two years later, Muriel and Sydney were divorced.</p><p>In 1992 Betty Box received the first UK Women in Film lifetime achievement award. She died of cancer at her home in Gerrard's Cross on 15 January 1999. After her divorce, Muriel Box co-founded Femina, Britain's first feminist publishing house, and became a campaigner for women's rights, working with her friend, Edith Summerskill, the Labour politician, to reform Britain's divorce laws. In 1970 she married Gerald Gardiner, the Lord Chancellor. She died on 18 May 1991.</p><p>In 2012 <em>To Dorothy a Son </em>was, unaccountably, released on DVD.</p><p><em>© Rachel Cooke 2013</em></p><!-- Guardian Watermark: internal-code/content/418962817|2013-10-07T10:05:55Z|281261806e67175a6ad949305ed2caa256259e09 -->",
