      "id":"music/2013/oct/05/jay-z-review-manchester",
      "sectionId":"music",
      "sectionName":"Music",
      "webPublicationDate":"2013-10-05T18:00:03Z",
      "webTitle":"Jay Z – review",
      "webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/music/2013/oct/05/jay-z-review-manchester",
      "apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/music/2013/oct/05/jay-z-review-manchester",
      "fields":{
        "newspaperPageNumber":"23",
        "trailText":"<p>Solo, Jay Z is short of the sparkle seen in his 2011 live shows with Kanye West, writes <strong>Kitty Empire</strong></p>",
        "headline":"Jay Z – review",
        "body":"<p>It's hard to shake the feeling that something might be missing at the first night of Jay Z's Magna Carter world tour. It's not wordplay, of course. The Magna Carter tour makes plain the pun on Jay's surname (Carter), merely latent on his most recent album, <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/music/2013/jul/07/jay-z-magna-carta-holy-grail-review\" title=\"\"><em>Magna Carta Holy Grail</em></a>. \"Minglin' in England\", runs the legend on a hoodie at the merch stall. During a show that runs nearly two hours, there is no shortage of versifying, drawing on <em>MCHG</em> and Jay Z's muscular corpus of past works.</p><p>We get Tom Ford, <em>MCHG</em>'s designer-praising standout cut, in which the rapper has \"spent all his euros on tuxes and weird clothes\". We also get <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/music/musicblog/2012/may/18/jay-z-dead-presidents\" title=\"\">Dead Presidents II</a>, from Jay Z's 1996 debut, <em>Reasonable Doubt</em>, in which Carter's dollar gross \"at the end of the fiscal year\" was, at the time of writing, more of an aspiration than the fact it is now <a href=\"http://www.therichest.com/celebnetworth/celeb/rappers/jay-z-net-worth/\" title=\"\">$500m</a> (estimated last year). Apparently, Beyoncé and <a href=\"http://www.nme.com/news/jay-z/72987\" title=\"\">Blue Ivy</a>™ are backstage.</p><p>News outlets widely reported that Timbaland – the producer Tim Mosley, whose work with Jay Z, Missy Elliott, Justin Timberlake et al sculpted the imperial phase of US pop&nbsp;of the late 90s and early 00s – would be<a href=\"http://www.nme.com/news/jay-z--3/72786\" title=\"\"> supporting Jay in Europe</a>. Instead, the flow of fans into the not-quite-sold-out arena is accompanied by faceless DJing. When Timbaland does appear, the super producer is one &nbsp;of three live band members manning small industrial units of sound gear during Jay Z's set. (A drummer at the top of a high-rise geometric set completes the backing&nbsp;group.)</p><p>\"DJ Timmy Tim\", as Jay fondly refers to him, is here in part because Jay's <em>Magna Carta…  </em>is as much his historic document as it is Jay's. You could argue that Mosley's stark, restless beats are one of the best things about <em>MCHG</em>, controversially released via a smartphone in July. Jay's verses occasionally tread water – water that is, admittedly, very high; Mosley's beats end a period in the semi-wilderness for the producer that peaked with a falling out with American music's premier mogul-poet. FuckWithMeYouknowIGotIt is one of <em>MCHG</em>'s best grandstanding moments. But its cockiness could apply equally to Tim's beat as it does to Jay's verse, laden with mafia-themed Italian.</p><p>When Jay goes off for a short shirt-swapping break, Timbaland shows off how he builds a track, beat-boxing, layering digitals. It turns into an Aaliyah song. This is interlude heaven for the nerds. Others make for the loos. As expected, though, <a href=\"http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=7Va94E4Yetk\" title=\"\">Big&nbsp;Pimpin'</a> &nbsp;(a hit for Jay in 2000) is one of the night's high points. Having the man who minted the nagging Middle Eastern hook on stage just ices the cake.</p><p>What's missing here is the frisson that a real sparring partner brings. The last time Jay toured the UK's arenas, he was in the company of Kanye West, triumphantly showing off the pair's 2011 <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/music/2011/aug/14/jay-z-kanye-throne-review\" title=\"\"><em>Watch the Throne</em></a><em> </em>album. The two rappers battled from the top of huge hydraulic pillars, with footage of sharks, assailants and explosions projected on to them. Last summer, Jay circled the US (with a pit stop in London) in the company of Justin Timberlake – two very different showmen, united by their ability to look good in suits (and sound good on Timbaland beats). More recently, Jay's guest spot on Timberlake's recent <a href=\"http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=rCw50Loy7O4\" title=\"\">Murder</a> track ignited a minor furore when Carter took the name of <a href=\"http://www.theatlanticwire.com/entertainment/2013/09/yoko-ono-doesnt-care-that-jay-z-dissed-her/69859/\" title=\"\">Yoko Ono</a> in vain.</p><p>However masterful a rapper Jay Z remains – and he is particularly electrifying on the third quarter of the set – Jay on his own feels like a slight comedown from these recent extravaganzas. The pauses between tracks stretch a little uncomfortably, too, probably due to first-night adjustments. West would have said something outrageous by now; Jay resorts to the time-honoured \"Manchester make some noise!\"</p><p>The visual spectacle is some compensation. Where Jay Z was an early evolver from the turntables-and-microphone era of rap, tonight's visuals are a considerable further step up from previous solo tours. Nervous projections use surveillance camera footage and explosions (viewed remotely) to engender a sense&nbsp;of fraughtness; one not undercut by what&nbsp;might be footage of the underside of a washing machine being&nbsp;photocopied.</p><p>It is probably unfair to expect something more than an arena show of an arena show. But you long for something extraordinary from Jay Z. In July, he performed <a href=\"http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=p6WpZeo93qQ\" title=\"\">Picasso Baby for &nbsp;six hours in New York's Pace Gallery</a>, sending at least one art critic&nbsp;into <a href=\"http://www.vulture.com/2013/07/jerry-saltz-face-to-face-with-jay-z.html\" title=\"\">raptures</a>. That performance was, admittedly, a riff on a piece by <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/artanddesign/jonathanjonesblog/2013/jul/31/jonathan-jones-blog-marina-abramovic\" title=\"\">Marina Abramovic</a> (with their rampant ancestor-worship, rappers know all about quoting other artists). It was criticised by <a href=\"http://www.newyorker.com/online/blogs/sashafrerejones/2013/07/jay-z-this-charming-man.html\" title=\"\">some</a> as being an elitist gimmick, but the intensity with&nbsp;which Jay Z reportedly&nbsp;embraced the performance, his willingness to go eyeball to eyeball with strangers for so many hours, served to underline why this rapper is just so much more than the sum of his many business interests (to which he has recently added: sports agent). Tonight, Jay Z is never less than fully committed to every word. But when he asks us to throw our diamonds in the air for the umpteenth time, this routine could use a little buffing.</p><!-- Guardian Watermark: internal-code/content/419083051|2013-10-07T10:05:55Z|bdab815dec9f2f15fbc0432b58453941f122a3fc -->",
